    Objectives

    Apply dimension reduction and clustering methods to various datasets. Visualize and validate clustering.

    Marking

    This assignment is marked on a total of 30 points: 10 points for problem 1, 20 points for problem 2.

    (Remember that in the final mark, all assignments will be rescaled to have the same weight).

    Libraries

    It is your responsibility to install all the libraries required for this assignment in your environment

    function name (package name)
fviz_nbclust,fviz_cluster,fviz_dend (factoextra)
speccl       (clusterSim)
kmeans,hclust (stats)
NbClust (NbClust)


    You can install packages like this (for example)
    install.packages("NbClust",dependencies = TRUE)

    #?fviz_dend

    Plots

    Unless specified otherwise, use the base ‘plot’ function when you are asked to do a plot.

    e.g.

    plot(xp,col=km$clusters)

    Preliminary

    You will need to install the following libraries, if not already available in your environment:

    set.seed(123)
require(clusterSim)

    ## Loading required package: MASS

    Problem 1: [10 pts]

    In this problem, we will be comparing several clustering methods to see how they perform on various types of simulated datasets. The clusterSim package is useful in this respect because it allows us to quickly generate toy datasets. I am asking you to look at the clusterSim documentation :

    https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/clusterSim/clusterSim.pdf

    Hint: look for ‘shapes’ in the index of the package documentation. You should see functions that allow you to simulate 3 circles or two moons. As you know, most packages come with examples of R codes to tell you how to use the functions.

    So, you will be copying and pasting code from the documentation to answer to some questions of this assignment. This method is very useful. Almost always, you will be using it to get familiar with the working of any new R package that you want to use.

    As per the clustering methods, I will ask you to use the ‘kmeans’ function for the k-means clustering method and the ‘speccl’ function for the spectral clustering method.

    You will also have to calculate principal components. For this, you can use the function ‘prcomp’.

    As usual, unless a specific instruction tells you otherwise, use functions with the minimal number of arguments. This means that you will rely on default values for non-specified arguments.

    Q1 [1 pt]

    Look at the documentation of the clusterSim package (pdf link above). Find and execute a single line of code that computes the shapes of two moons.

    Look in the manual for a function that generates a data set containing two clusters with untypical shapes (similar to waxing and waning crescent moon).

    This will create an object called ‘stm’. Use the exact same code as in the documentation. The number of objects in stm will be equal to 180.

    # do not remove this line
set.seed(1245)
# your 1 line of code below
stm<-shapes.two.moon(180)

    Plot ‘stm’ as is done in the ‘clusterSim’ package manual. This is one line of code that uses the plot function and applies it to the ‘data’ field of the ‘stm’ object. It uses a color field called rainbow(2) applied to the clusters of ‘stm’. Use the exact same code as found in the documentation.

    plot(stm$data,col=rainbow(2)[stm$clusters])

    Q2 [1 pt]

    Now we will repeat the same exercise with another shape.

    Find the function that generates a data set containing three clusters with untypical ring shapes (circles).

    Create an object called ‘sc3b’ which stores the shapes of 3 circles, then plot it.

    Copy and paste the code of the documentation and modify slightly the code to make sure that

    1. you use 130, 200 and 300 points on each circle instead of the original values (c(120,180,240)) found in the manual.
    2. you add the argument pch=19 when you call the plot function.
    # do not erase this line

# your 2 lines of code below

    ---

    Since this x has much more number of columns than its number of rows. And also, its 3000 columns can be consider as high dimensional data, since 3000 is a relatively big number.

    The elbow method

    Q4 (4 pts)

    We will use the ‘elbow’ or ‘knee’ method (choose the part of the body that you prefer) to estimate a reasonable value for the number of clusters ‘seen’ in the data.

    Hint: A similar (but not identical) problem is found at: https://uc-r.github.io/kmeans_clustering

    Your code will be different. Follow the instructions below.

    1. Create a function named wss, with a single argument named k, that compute the total within-cluster sum of square for any value of k. The body of the function should only contain one line of code. This line of code should compute a clustering of k clusters, using the kmeans function, and 10 random start. Your line of code should extract the tot.withinss member of the kmeans object.
    2. Use a for loop that calls the function wss for all values i between 1 and kmax=8, and append the result to an array named ‘wss_values’. Do not forget to initialize kmax to 8 and to initialize the ‘wss_values’ array to a NULL object before the loop. When the loop is finished, ‘wss_values’ should contain the total within-cluster sum of square for each value of i between 1 and kmax.
    3. Call the plot function to create the graph of wss_values(i) for i=1:kmax. Use type=‘b’, pch=19, a blue color, and the following labels for the x and y axis: “Number of clusters K”,“Total within-clusters sum of squares”. Add a single line of code to overlay a vertical red line that goes through the value i=4 (use function ‘abline’ with the ‘v’ and ‘col’ arguments).
    # keep these two lines
set.seed(123)
df=xp
#
# write a function to compute total within-cluster sum of square 
# (call kmeans and extract tot.withinss from the returned object)
# 
wss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(df, k, nstart = 10 )$tot.withinss
}

    NOTES:

    There is another contradiction between question and comments.

    In question, kmax = 8, in code comments, kmax = 15.

    We will do both here.

    1. KMAX = 8 as in the question asked:
    # Compute and plot wss for k = 1 to k = 15
# initialize kmax and wss_values
wss_values=NULL
kmax = 8


    loop for i =1 to kmax
    k.values <- 1:kmax
    for(k in k.values){
      wss_values=c(wss_values,wss(k))
    }
    

    plot(k.values, wss_values,
           type="b", pch = 19, col='blue', frame = FALSE,
           xlab="Number of clusters K",
           ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")
    

    abline(v=4, col='red')

    1. KMAX = 15 as the comments asked

      # Compute and plot wss for k = 1 to k = 15
# initialize kmax and wss_values
wss_values=NULL
kmax = 15


      loop for i =1 to kmax
      k.values <- 1:kmax
      for(k in k.values){
        wss_values=c(wss_values,wss(k))
      }

             type="b", pch = 19, col='blue', frame = FALSE,

             ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

    table(y, km4$cluster)
    ##    
## y   1 2 3 4
##   1 5 2 0 0
##   2 0 7 0 0
##   3 0 0 0 6
##   4 8 0 0 0
##   6 2 0 7 0

    Based on this confusion table, complete the following:


    The true label that corresponds to cluster 1 is : ?

    Label 4.

    The true label that corresponds to cluster 2 is : ?

    Label 2.

    The true label that corresponds to cluster 3 is : ?

    Label 6.


    The true label that corresponds to cluster 4 is : ?

    Label 3.

    Hint: use a majority rule over the rows for each column of the confusion table.

    For example, in the following example, the true label y=1 is associated twice with the computed cluster label c=1, and seven times with c=7. Therefore, the true label that corresponds to cluster c=1 is y=2. Similarly the true label associated with c=2 is y=3.

    c=1 c=2
    y=1 2 1
    y=2 7 2
    y=3 0 6

    c=1 c=2 … y=1 2 1 … y=2 7 2 … y=3 0 6 …

    Hierarchical clustering

    The function ‘hclust’ is very popular for fitting hierarchical clustering. It gives access to a choice of agglomeration methods:

    “ward.D”, “ward.D2”, “single”, “complete”, “average” (= UPGMA), “mcquitty” (= WPGMA), “median” (= WPGMC) or “centroid” (= UPGMC).

    #?hclust

    Cluster validation

    Q12 (1 pt)

    NbClust

    x <- read.table(file='xd.txt',header=TRUE)
pr.out=prcomp(x, scale=TRUE)
p=2
xp = pr.out$x[,1:p]
dfkeep=xp
#x

    Apply the function NbClust to the object dfkeep (saved above). Use diss=NULL, a euclidean distance, a minimum number of cluster of 2, a maximum number of clusters of 11, the kmeans method, index=‘all’ and a value of 0.1 for alphaBeale. Save the result in an object called ‘nb’.

    library(NbClust)
nb <- NbClust(
dfkeep, 
diss=NULL, 
distance = "euclidean", 
min.nc=2, max.nc=11, method = "kmeans", 
index = "all", alphaBeale = 0.1)

    ## *** : The Hubert index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters.
##                 In the plot of Hubert index, we seek a significant knee that corresponds to a 
##                 significant increase of the value of the measure i.e the significant peak in Hubert
##                 index second differences plot. 
## 

    ## *** : The D index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters. 
##                 In the plot of D index, we seek a significant knee (the significant peak in Dindex
##                 second differences plot) that corresponds to a significant increase of the value of
##                 the measure. 
##  
## ******************************************************************* 
## * Among all indices:                                                
## * 4 proposed 2 as the best number of clusters 
## * 6 proposed 3 as the best number of clusters 
## * 6 proposed 4 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 5 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 8 as the best number of clusters 
## * 1 proposed 9 as the best number of clusters 
## * 2 proposed 10 as the best number of clusters 
## * 2 proposed 11 as the best number of clusters 
## 
##                    ***** Conclusion *****                            
##  
## * According to the majority rule, the best number of clusters is  3 
##  
##  
## *******************************************************************

    Apply the table function to the first row of the Best.nc member of ‘nb’. This will show how many votes the algorithm gives for each candidate value of k (the unknown number of clusters)

    table(nb$Best.nc[1,])
    ## 
##  0  1  2  3  4  5  8  9 10 11 
##  2  1  4  6  6  1  1  1  2  2

    Question 14 [1 pt]

    Gap statistic for hierarchical clustering

    Apply the clusGap function to object dfkeep. Use a value of hcut for the FUN argument, K.max=10 and B=10 Save the returned value to an object named ‘gap_stat’. Then apply the function fviz_gap_stat to this object to visualize the gap statistics variation with k.

    #gap...
#fviz...
gap_stat = clusGap(dfkeep, FUN = hcut, K.max = 10, B = 10)
fviz_gap_stat(gap_stat)

    What is the value of k that maximizes the gap statistics?

    K = 4 maximize the gap statistics.
